A longer index that the rot is a sign of low risk of cancer
The men who have the index more than the rot are exposed to a lower risk of prostate cancer.
It is the surprising conclusion of a study published on Wednesday by the British magazine Cancer.
This may depend on the level of the male hormone testosterone.
"our findings show that the relative length of the finger is simple test of risk of prostate cancer, particularly for men for 60 years," proclaimed the co-author of the study Ros Eeles, a professor at the Institute for cancer research at the University of Warwick.
The finger could help to determine which men would have to take the test for prostate cancer, including by combining with the genetic risk or other factors aggrâvants as the antécedents family health, Eeles added.
During the 1994-2009 period she has followed with his colleagues in Britain more than 1500 prostate cancer patients and healthy nearly three thousand men at the same time.
More than half of the participants in the study had the index of the right hand shorter than the rot.
For them and for the 19 percent of those who had the fingers of the same length, we found the same probability of a prostate cancer.
In the case of those who had the greater that the rot the risk, however, is down to 33 percent for men 60 years before the reduction of the risk was 87 percent.
The report for the length of two fingers - trained during the prenatal period - different levels of sex hormones that the child in the womb.
Less testosterone is a longer index.
Previous research had shown that it is precisely the testosterone that development aid of a prostate cancer.
The pprofesseur Vacla Paces, Czech Geneticist renowned and former president of the Academy of Sciences, KTC that he is aware of this study, but that, apparently, he did not think that the relationship between the length of his fingers and cancer is "completely demonstrated."
