Obama puts a brake on new oil rigs
There is no new oil drilling in the Gulf of Mexico off the coast of Florida, State of the south-east of the United States, in the years to come.
The government of Washington made a ban A equivalent ban and, thus, definitively abolished its original plans.
Even new drilling off the Atlantic coast, remain for the time being banned.
The Secretary of the Interior Ken Salazar made the announcement on Wednesday.
That is, in April, the explosion of the Deepwater Horizon drilling platform "'which is at the root of this ban. it must remain in force at least for the next five years.
Facing this accident that claimed the lives of eleven employees and led to the worst environmental disaster in the United States, President Barack Obama, under pressure from the opposition and of this sector of activity, said he was willing to allow the implementation of new drilling in the eastern part of the Gulf of Mexico.
The supporters of this solution want to reduce the US dependence on foreign countries for supplies of oil.
The question of who bears the responsibility of the devastating oil spill in the Gulf is not, to date, finally resolved.
The British oil group, which is facing multi-billion compensation claims, is at the centre of the accusations.
A committee of inquiry set up by Obama must submit its conclusions in December.
In October, the Secretary of the Interior Ken Salazar had lifted the freeze of the drilling imposed after the explosion of the platform.
As a result of this decision, oil groups had submitted requests for new drilling projects.
With stricter controls and tougher safety measures, Obama and Salazar want to prevent another disaster.
The competent supervisory authority, which was discredited after many accusations of corruption, is currently the subject of in-depth reforms.
At the same time, Mr Obama announced the lucrative tax breaks for oil and gas groups.
The actors of this sector of activity now publicly warn against the fact that the flow of food in the Gulf would be much lower than this is the case until now.
"the government's objective is to put a brake on the rapid growth of the oil and gas sector" depending on the outcome of a current survey carried out in the sector by the audit firm BDO, before the drilling ban on Wednesday.
Moreover, the American Enery Alliance regret the uncertainty which characterises this sector: "Nobody knows exactly what will change with the regulation."
The investments made in support of new projects have been postponed until further notice, to the detriment of growth.
