On the side of the river Bodo-Jetty, Esther Badom said that, once, there was shrimp by whole buckets here.
But in the meantime the calm waters have completely exhausted.
Five years ago, a huge amount of oil has been building up of a pipeline which has exploded in the vast swamp.
Fishermen living in the nearby town of Bodo must now pull for six hours to reach the fishing grounds: The Ogoni countries located at the heart of the Niger Delta is regarded as one of the most polluted regions in the world.
The full extent of the devastation is plain to see leafing through the marshes of mangrove forests by watercourses.
Instead of a clear water, the motor boat out brown water cradingue. anyone who has his hand cut off any covered in oil.
The roots of small mangrove forests are emerging as sticks of pipes. the isolated palm trees are sadly hang their diver.
We look in vain for the clouds of birds, as practised in the wetlands: Dés motors stop, a bizarre silence in this paradise of old who looks like a petrol station by the smell.
"what is happening here, it is war against the environment," says Mr Celestine Akpobari sad air: "Our life is characterised by a constant danger with regard to health."
The comparison is made.
The region where the Ogoni people live is a battlefield besieged for dozens of years: more than 60 years ago, the first European explorers have penetrated here; the first was held in the 1980 s by Ken Saro-Wiwa. that was carried out later. in 1993, the group Shell had to interrupt its production activities in this region because they had become very dangerous for its employees.
Even today, the Ogoni return is prohibited in this society: As more than 2 million barrel of oil are being siphoned off on a daily basis through more than 5000 oil wells and 7000 kilometres of pipelines in the whole of the Delta region, three times as large as Switzerland, the country's oil fields Ogoni are untapped, because the situation is too unstable oil for this group.
Every few hundred metres in water tréteaux steel as bizarre sculptures: The very affectionate "Christmas trees" refers to the head of drilling holes.
They have up to 50 years, most are being undermined by corrosion until reference.
Akpobari believes that a drilling of this nature is broken piece from time to time, as a steady stream of crude oil flows in the water.
According to the experts' estimates, more than two billion litres spilled on the ecosystem in 50 years: Every year, the quantity of oil equivalent to that which has passed in the sea at the accident of super-pétrolier "Exxon Valdez" 21 years ago off the coast of Alaska, one of the biggest environmental disaster in the history of humanity.
Who is responsible for the persistent environmental pollution? the answer to this question divides the player.
For the Shell Group, the siphonage and sabotage of oil pipelines are responsible for more than 90 percent of the pollution. environmentalists consider the explosions of drilling and oil pipelines perforated as the main causes.
In 2008, the American scientist Richard Steiner blamed the Shell Group to enforce safety standards in Nigeria essentially less strict than anywhere else in the world: Only the failure rate of pipeline-owners was "still much higher than alleures."
Some emerging forms of wetlands to a place that, from afar, looks like an abandoned workshop, full of work and installed at fresh air: They are completely naked and covered in to work.
A fire scintille under one of the many barrels that sometimes associated with pipes, sometimes scattered without charge on the site must be répérés illegal: a small refinery.
It was heat the crude oil in the lines for several hours, "says Michael, the team leader.
Initially, gasoline enters a container through pipes, then, to the end of the conduct of kerosene tombent drops and you have finally diesel.
That is how Michael and his four FoPs produce every day four barrels of 300 litres of diesel: "We grosses $34 000 Naira," approximately $22.
Delta residents take advantage of the chronic shortage of fuel in the largest producer of oil in black Africa.
Nigeria has only one refinery.
The illegal refiners can sell at a cheaper price than ridiculously low of just 40 euro cents per litre of diesel: Because they acquire gratuitement their raw material.
This is provided by the "protectors" which the network of oil pipelines in successful Ogoni all across the country. according to the experts, the country loses in this way at least 16 million litres of crude oil in the whole of the Niger Delta.
Only a small completely insignificant part of the raw material stored provisionally is illegally purifiée: organised crime networks which are also among its members of military officials, politicians and take the lion's share of tankers and the selling off on the world market.
The militant Akpobari considers that the debate on the question of whether to assign the environmental disaster or rather the subversive activities to the population or the lax mode of production is purely academic.
"if the oil companies were not seen as intruders and if the livelihoods of the fishermen were not so deeply destroyed, there would be no sabotage or theft and illegal refineries."
But the relations of the Ogoni, weakness, especially to Shell have deteriorated so much that it was no longer any question that the withdrawal of the group. "perhaps that operators with other nationalities, such as Chinese, will be better."
Then, Michael became nervous.
"it is high time that you déguerpissiez" robust oil worker.
"the soldiers can occur at any time."
If the illegal refiners are surprised by the special units of the armed forces, they will not be the subject of an arrest, but at most they will offer bribes.
Even the soldiers above all from the north of the country to benefit as the raw material of all Nigerians.
"at any point of view, this rotten trick our country," Akpori regret.
