Mysterious work of Caterpillar
The International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) provides new indications for a nuclear program developed by Syria.
But this country refuses to take a position on this subject, let alone to submit to the controls of the agency.
On the night of 5 to 6 September 2007 to midnight, at least four Israeli F- 15 I fighter planes attacked a mysterious form design on the Syrian territory.
It is on the side of the euphrate; the largest city near is at 30 kilometres is Dair as-Sur.
His name appears in the IAEA documents, because it is a question of the reactor that Syria has reportedly built with the help of North Korea in parallélépipède of stone, hidden in a valley marked by the absence of electrical power.
According to a briefing of the intelligence services of the United States, the CIA, dating from the end of April 2008, the reactor, known as the name of the nearby el-Kibar, would be able to produce plutonium for atomic weapons.
However, this technique is valid since the 1950 s.
The CIA has shown a video presentation of satellite images.
Through computer-assisted animation, they indicated that the likely location of each component of the reactor before the destruction of the plant which represents a miniature copy of the nord-Coréen model of the Yongbyon nuclear plant.
In addition, she has presented the photos showing the building, even within it.
It seems that the reactor was about to be put into service, but it was not yet equipped for fuel rods.
Today, more than three years after the Israeli bombing, barely more information than is available at the time, and even, with the time more and more the mystery deepens.
The former US President George W. Bush has revealed in his memoirs that before the attack, the CIA was sure that Syria had built a reactor to el-Kibar peu' indications this country, but was "an active nuclear weapons program."
Some intelligence agents in Europe prefer to be more careful about this and speak only a "deemed" reactor, even if they see the presentation of the CIA as "plausible."
They have a lack of evidence, as well as to the IAEA.
Asked about how it ensures that it has a nuclear reactor, a high-ranking diplomat of the United Nations has just given a terse response in summer by saying that the IAEA had enough of "documents to ask questions."
The Syrian have certainly kidnapped with haste the rubble of the "unused military building" and proceeded to an orderly resolution of the ground.
However, in June 2008, a team of IAEA experts led by the former chief inspector Oli Heinonen, discovered to el-Kibar traces of uranium produced by men.
In addition, the IAEA has received thanks to a Member State commercial providers of satellite images showing the time took the attaque. it seems that charterparties are more eloquent than those presented by the CIA.
However, these photos are not available on the market because the anonymous sponsor, perhaps Israel, has the exclusivity.
It is impossible for the IAEA to determine their authenticity objectively.
Syria has always ensured that she had never made a secret nuclear programme and that it had not built reactor.
Damascus maintains that uranium found at the site comes from weapons used by Israel.
But the IAEA has rejected this argument after the analysis of the particles as implausible.
Since that time, damas refuses any discussion on this issue, as on satellite images.
In addition, Syria does not allow the controllers to carry out a second inspection on the site of el-Kibar and denied access to the rubble of the building destroyed by the bomb.
But, even Israel retains a stubborn silence.
Confirming the official position, Ehud Olmert, then Prime Minister at the time of the attack, said recently: "We will never comments on this subject."
That is how the investigation of this matter has been dragging on since June 2008 without a result and that it "is increasingly turning into a serious problem of credibility of the Agency," as acknowledged by a high-ranking Western diplomat in service at the IAEA headquarters in Vienna, he is a serious violation of the treaty banning nuclear weapons.
The IAEA considers that to achieve progress, the existence of three other facilities must have "a functional report" with the alleged reactor.
So far, the inspectors did not indicate what kind of facilities it is or what is their function or suspected to contain.
According to reports published by the newspaper Süddeutsche Zeitung ', they are known within the IAEA respectively under the names of Marj as-Sultan, Masyaf and Iskandariayah also the name of nearby towns.
The independent Institute for Science and International Security Institute (International Institute of Science and International Security) of Washington has identified these localities and discovered on satellite images of a complex close to Masyaf which is likely to be one of the suspects.
It is possible that he is in a military base or directly next to it; this is exactly the reason why Syria refuses access of the three sites to IAEA inspectors.
In Vienna, it states that the Syrians are afraid that the inspection group is in fact spies who would be sent on behalf of the United States by the IAEA to spy on military installations.
In fact, it is an intelligence provided by the American secret agents who attracted the attention of nuclear inspectors.
The IAEA has the information, including satellite photos, that the vehicles have made shuttles between the three sites and the parallélépipède stone in transporting substances.
A senior Western diplomat said in Vienna that at least one of the facilities could "be used to fuel production."
He would not "information on sensitive activities," such as uranium enrichment and reprocessing; processes that are essential to the production of atomic weapons.
This type of reactor works certainly thanks to not enriched uranium.
Nevertheless, there is to the rigour of plausible assumptions regarding the following fundamental questions: where should have come where would we separate plutonium and uranium needed for the production of the bomb.
We do not know if the rubble, which could hide traces of great value, were stored in the three sites.
When the hundreds of trucks LFIS vanish, nobody will have information on the place of storage of rubble.
For the IAEA, it is unlikely that Syria has made al-Tibni examine the salt mine in 1998, only a few kilometres of el-Kibar, on the other side of the Tigris, to see if it can agree on the storage of radioactive waste.
Recently afdeling satellite pictures for the famous magazine Jane's, the former inspector of the IAEA, Mr Robert Kelley has established a link between them and the reactor in question.
However, satellite photos show that Syria has undertaken of earth-moving work in the three sites suspects and displaced huge containers when the IAEA started to demand access to these places.
It is possible that this is a coincidence, but this has not contributed to remove the suspicions.
In in diplomatic circles, it is said that the IAEA has spent several months to draw up a plan for the inspections to be carried out. this plan should allow Syria to preserve any military secrets. only time invested shows how great the inspectors interest in this matter.
Meanwhile, Damascus has also responded to this proposal.
A year ago, if the Western diplomats in Vienna did not state of the destruction of the reactor, the emergency would not be reported for this matter, "says, for example, Glyn Davies, the ambassador of the United States a few months since what is known as the special inspections, one of the most powerful tools available to the International Atomic Energy Agency to implement its controls.
The director of the IAEA, Mr Yukiya Amano, who had to propose these inspections, has already spoken of "an option to which I am open to the future," but it is still.
This means there is a huge risk: on the one hand, it requires a majority in the Council of Governors of the IAEA and many of the 35 countries represented there have no desire to see the situation escalate.
On the other hand, as réflechir diplomat: "At this point, if at the end they do not find anything"
