The Democratic routine
Support for democracy in Latin America continues to increase, as well as to private enterprise.
The crime has become a greater concern than unemployment.
And Brazil is seen as more influential than the US in much of the region.
These are some of the conclusions of the latest poll Latinobarómetro taken in 18 countries and published exclusively by The Economist.
Since the survey was conducted on a regular basis since 1995, it follows the changes of attitude in the region.
Two elements stand out of this year's results of the survey, conducted in September and early October.
The first is the relatively sunny mood of Latin America.
The second is the growing stability of attitudes towards democracy and its key institutions.
The support for democracy has increased significantly in several countries on the Pacific rim of South America (see Table 1).
For example, in Peru, where economic growth has averaged 6% per year since 2002, support for democracy has gone from a minimum of 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
It has also increased in Mexico, where the economy rebounded after a sharp decline in production last year.
But only about half of the respondents in Mexico and Brazil, the two most populous countries of the region, are convinced Democrats, which lowers the regional average (see Table 2).
Some 44% of respondents from the region said they were satisfied with the way democracy in their countries worked in practice; it is the same figure as last year but with a sharp increase on the 25% in 2001 (Chart 3)
Some 34% said they had confidence in the Parliament of their country and 45% in their government, the same as last year in both cases; but rising sharply compared to 2003 (17% and 24% respectively).
Ten years ago, the economic problems in Latin America have shaken the support for democracy.
If it has lasted for the global financial crisis, it is certainly due to the fact that many of store-survey was a brief recession and benefited from a strong recovery.
In addition, a network of social security has helped to protect the poor.
(the United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America reported this week that the proportion of Latin Americans living in poverty have risen only slightly in 2009 and has fallen again this year, to 32%.)
But the mood varies considerably from one country to another (see Chart 4).
Brazil's good economic performance and the popularity of its outgoing president, Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva, is reflected by a widely shared sense of progress
What is more rare in Mexico and Central America where the recession has been more severe and where the violent crimes have increased.
It is only the second time since the survey began more than respondents across Latin America as a whole have cited the crime rather than unemployment as the most important issue for their country (see Table 5).
Approximately 31% say that they or one of their close have been the victim of a crime in the past year; however, this figure is down from 38% last year and is the lowest since 1995.
A more robust economic performance is reflected in the rise in support of the private company and the market economy: approximately 71% of respondents from the region say that private enterprise is essential for the development, against 56% in 2007 (see Chart 6).
Some 58% of the market economy is the only system that will make their developed country, against 47% last year.
Interestingly, 62% of respondents in Venezuela are of this opinion (and 80% support private enterprise); even if their left-wing president, Hugo Chavez, take many private companies.
Brazil is the greatest leader in the region, mentioned by respondents (19% against 18% last year), followed by the United States (9%, unchanged from last year) and Venezuela (9%, down by 11% since last year)
But the United States are considered the most influential country by the respondents in Mexico and in most of Central America, while Venezuela has this distinction in Ecuador, the Dominican Republic and Nicaragua.
A vote tainted
Nobody expected to hold general elections in Haiti on November 28.
But it was much worse than the "outsiders" who wanted to help the affected countries and in fear.
Ballot papers were presented of ballot boxes and a new ballot, scattered in the goutières, polling stations ransacked and intimidation
The polling stations open late in the evening.
Many of Hatïens, including many who were displaced following the earthquake in January, had slipped in the neighbourhood finding out where to vote.
Some of them were eventually abandoned.
A dozen of presidential candidates, including several alleged favorites, have denounced the fraud and have called for the annulment of the election.
Protests, sometimes violent, have exploded across the country.
Nevertheless, Edmond Mulet, the top official in Haiti to the United Nations, sees the event as "a fair election in many respects."
Observers from the Organization of American States and the Caribbean Community said cautiously that they do not "believe that these irregularities, as serious as they are, necessarily had invalidated the process."
In other words, the show continues.
The electoral authority, the opponents are beholden to René Préval, outgoing President unpopular, and its candidate, Jude Célestin, must announce preliminary results on 7 December.
The expected second round is scheduled for January.
All hope is not lost in the election.
The two opposition candidates, Michel Martelly, a rap musician, and Mirlande Manigat, a former first lady, withdrew from their initial appeal for the vote to be declared invalid.
But there may be problems if Mr Célestin, who has little or no support among voters, is declared by the electoral authority as having reached the second toura reached the second round.
With a cholera epidemic, and more than 1 million earthquake survivors who are still living in tents, it was feared that the participation would be.
Myself, many Haitïens wanted to vote but were prevented from doing so because of the disruption.
Almost 250 000, needed for voting, identity cards were not distributed shortly before the election.
The issue is important.
The donors see the election of a popular and legitimate government as an important step in the reconstruction of Haiti.
And so, it is clear, the Haitians themselves.
The toes to the center
The weeks after having become suddenly widow, Cristina Fernández, Argentina's President, has benefited from a wave of public sympathy that has improved its approval rating of 20 points, to more than 50%; it is to its highest level since it was elected in 2007.
Yet turn this into a successful campaign for a second term in an election next year could depend on the choice of Mrs Fernández, clearly in mourning, that it would abandon the intransigence of her deceased husband or not, former political partner and predecessor, Néstor Kirchner.
And, in this regard, the signs remain unclear.
Mr Kirchner, who has continued to manage the economic policy, even after his wife takes as chairman, had the habit of making budgets which under-appreciate its tax revenue, economic growth and inflation.
This has resulted in the first couple of spending the extra money at will.
Ms Fernandez's government lost its majority in Congress last year, on paper.
But the opposition is divided, and the situation has fallen into disarray following the death of Mr Kirchner of a heart attack on October 27.
Some of the members of the ruling Peronist movement dissidents to Mrs Fernández.
But after the chaotic sessions (where a parliamentarian in the face one of his peers and others have accused the government of corruption), the Congress does not have to approve the 2011 budget.
"I am not going to fight," said the president.
Currently, the 2010 budget will be implemented next year, leaving the president still more room for manoeuvre to spend at will.
The economy overheating widely: it is likely to grow by nearly 9% this year.
The official rate of inflation now stands at 11.1% but many private estimates and the wage claims of trade unions, this figure close to 30%.
Mr Kirchner, who took office in 2003 when Argentina feared an economic collapse, has made it a priority to growth and poverty reduction, rather than the control of inflation.
It has refused to deal with the IMF, it has harassed the private sector and served the INDEC, the statistical office, which has carried out falsifications of official statistics on inflation.
Mrs Fernandez to moderate these policies?
It has called for talks between private companies and the union leaders.
And its officials say that they want to limit wage increases next year to 18%.
The economy has been driven by high world prices of Argentina's agricultural exports.
But inflation has eroded the boost to growth following a sharp devaluation in 2002.
This is perhaps the reason why Mrs Fernandez shows signs of wanting to restore the financial relations of Argentina to the rest of the world.
This year, the government has concluded an agreement with bondholders who had refused an earlier restructuring of the debt on which Argentina had not settled its deadlines in 2001.
Now Ms Fernandez seems to be edging towards year agreement with creditor governments grouped in the Paris Club, to which it owes some $6,7 trillion.
The Kirchners have always insisted on the fact that this could involve surveillance by the IMF, as is custom.
But last month, Amado Boudou, the Minister of Economic Affairs, has announced that the fund would provide a "technical assistance" to design a new national consumer price index; what looks like a prelude to the clean-up of the INDEC.
It is not clear if Mrs Fernandez wants to stay in politics beyond the end of its mandate, now that her husband is no longer with him.
If it does, it needs to win the support of the middle class, among which the kirchnerisme is very advocated.
When Argentines will be returned from their summer holidays in Mars, the wave of sympathy for it has fallen.
If she wants to win another election, she will have to decide whether to repudiate, without noise, many of the policies of her husband.
A demi-hourra for China
The Taiwanese voters are geared towards a kind of a closer union with the mainland.
What Taiwan think of its big brother on the other side of the Straits?
More than 7.5 million voters are presented on November 27, or 70% of eligible persons, to elect mayors and councillors in five urban districts, in the framework of what is regarded as a general assessment of the president, Ma Ying-jeou.
Mr. Ma is itself become a substitute for the feelings from the continent, with innovative business ties, including a partial free trade pact, in the largest reorganization of relations with China since 1949.
Mr Ma pass the test, but only just.
Although his party Kuomintang (KMT) has won three of the five local authorities, it has failed to win a majority of the votes.
Instead, the démocrate-progressiste Party (DPP), which has opted for the independence of Taiwan, won nearly 50% of all the votes for the KMT of 45%.
If this had been a presidential elections, Mr Ma would be in difficulty.
Since he was elected two years ago, the part of his party's vote has fallen by about 8%.
For the first time, the DPP has drawn voters, even with the KMT in the municipal councils.
The event has revealed most of the main topics of Taiwanese elections, including lorries to aggressive campaign and flags of mass rally with girls who danced in holding.
An undeclinable mysterious assassination attempt has also been carried out.
Sean Lien, Lien Chan's son, honorary president of the KMT election, has done a tour for a KMT candidate on the eve of the election.
A man of the crowd has fired on the young Mr Lien, purely through the face, injuring and killing a bystander.
Strangely, it has not been determined whether the sniper wanted to hurt to Mr Lien or settle a dispute with the candidate.
In any case, said Tsai Ing-wen, the leader of the PDP, the murder has had an impact on the election in the suspicion on the DPP leader and in ccsa.ca. electors to the KMT.
Perhaps the biggest winner of the elections was China.
It was striking that the question of the continent itself was absent.
Instead, the candidates have been with the plans for public housing and job creation.
Taiwan usually enjoys de facto independence and hate the military threat from China.
Thus, the KMT tends to avoid putting its links with the government in Beijing.
But this time, the DPP has also failed to stir up anti-Chinese sentiment.
This is the answer to a new awareness that Chinese companies are essential to the economic survival of Taiwan.
Mr Ma, for its part, has claimed a confirmation on whether its policy on China was acceptable to the Taiwanese majority.
It is expected that the government in Beijing continues to provide the commercial facilities, in accordance with its strategy to deceive Taiwan, of the eerie.
China has lost no time to send a negotiator to Taipei to organise a summit on the protection of investments and medical cooperation.
Certainly, she would also like to see a political integration; but let us start at the beginning.
It is better to wait until after the presidential election of 2012.
The DPP is reinventing itself.
Two years ago, it was bad: its former leader, Chen Shui-bian, had been sent to prison on charges of corruption.
President from 2000 to 2008, he was a provocateur in favour of an explicit independence.
But a new generation of moderates began under the leadership of Mrs Tsai and the PDP is working hard to attract professionals and young people.
Mrs Tsai was welcomed as a DPP candidate for the presidency, as Su Tseng-chang, who has served under Mr Chen.
Their party is doing its best to show that also can engage with Beijing.
Mrs Tsai announced plans for a panel of experts to act as a point of contact between the DPP and China, on condition that their talks can take place without preconditions.
Mrs Tsai tells the Taiwanese public that his party has a trustworthy "alternative" in relation to the hasty approach to Mr. Ma on China.
Mr Chen seems exasperated by this change.
In a statement issued from his cell, he said that the PDP candidate would have fared better if they insisted on the fact that Taiwan is a separate country.
He even ordered Mr Su, a pragmatic, not to run for the presidency.
Even without the intervention of Mr Chen, the DPP will find it hard to choose between its potential candidates.
The KMT introspection.
Mr Ma's assessments have been low, despite a sharp economic growth, the KMT candidate did not want to campaign with him.
His unpopularity seems to be largely due to unemployment and the widening of the gap between rich and poor.
A spokesman for the KMT said that his cabinet as well as local offices will be revised.
The PDP good results suggest that Taiwan's support for the rapprochement.
At the same time, the majority of Taiwanese see economic integration with China as inevitable.
According to Antonio Chiang, a prominent columnist, "the point of no return is already past."
