A microbe tolerant arsenic raises the possibility of new types of life on Earth, or elsewhere.
The discovery of a bizarre bacterium, which can use arsenic as one of its nutrients, broadens the scope for new forms of life on Earth and perhaps beyond.
Although the researchers found the unusual bacterium here on Earth, they say that this shows that the life opportunities beyond the major elements which were considered essential.
"this organization has a dual capacity."
"it can be developed either with phosphorus or with arsenic."
"that is why it is very special, even if it really is a form of life" foreign, "commented Paul Davies C. W. of the Arizona State University, co-author of the report contained in Thursday's online edition of the journal Science.
Six major elements have long been considered essential for life: carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, sulphur and phosphorus.
But the researchers found that the bacteria, found in the lake Mono, California, is able to continue to grow after having replaced the phosphorus by arsenic.
"we wondered what is still possible," said Ariel Anbar D. of Arizona State University, co-author of the report.
The discovery is important in the search for life beyond the Earth because researchers must be able to recognize the life, to know what life is like, said Anbar.
The study focuses on a microbe found on Earth.
However, the announcement of a press conference to discuss, which did not divulge the details of the discovery, has generated widespread speculation on the Internet that the report could disclose the discovery of extraterrestrial life.
This was not the case.
The discovery "shows that, in other environments, agencies might be able to use other elements to activate the biochemistry and that the whole" standard "elements, that we consider it absolutely necessary for life, could not be set," said Charles Cockell global, a professor at the Institute of Science and spacial, Open University, Milton Keynes, United Kingdom.
Cockell was not part of the research team.
"this work is new because it shows the substitution of one element to another in basic biochemistry and biochemical structure," added Cockell.
This was not a fortuitous discovery.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of the Institute of Astrologie of NASA, who led the study, has chosen the lake Mono because it has high levels of arsenic.
Phosphorus and arsenic are chemically similar; thus, she speculated that a microbe two substances could be in a position to replace the one to the other.
Arsenic is poisonous "mainly because its chemical behaviour is very similar to that of phosphorus."
"therefore, the agencies have struggled to distinguish these components separately."
"but arsenic is sufficiently different to that it does not exactly as the phosphorus; he got inside and, in some way, pulls together the work of our biochemical machine," said Anbar.
Researchers have collected the bacteria known as GFAJ- 1 and exposed to increasing concentrations of arsenic to which she was able to adapt and grow.
The microbe grows better with the phosphorus but the fact that he can live with arsenic in the place raises the possibility that a form of life using arsenic can occur naturally on Earth or on another planet or the moon where arsenic is more common.
Jamie S. Foster, an assistant professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, said that the idea that arsenic could be replaced by phosphorus was not new, but nothing has ever shown that it could walk.
Arsenic was most common at the beginning of the existence of the Earth, "she says, so the researchers have speculated that the first forms of life could use it.
This suggests that there may be other ways of the life, not just the way life on Earth was formed at the beginning, "said Foster, who was not part of the research team of Wolfe-Simon.
The research was funded by NASA, the Department of Energy and the National Institute of Health.
