Prosecutors do not inculperont Senator Ensign
The Department of Justice prosecutors have lifted the criminal charges brought on Senator John Ensign, arising from a matter related to an assistant of a former campaign and its efforts to obtain a work of lobbying for the husband of the woman, have anoncé the senator's lawyers on Wednesday.
The decision puts an end to the most serious legal threat faced by Mr Ensign, the Nevada Republican who was seen as a possible Republican candidate in the presidential election of 2012 until the scandal surrounding his case is the national headlines last year and damage his career.
The office of Mr Ensign said he was "very pleased" by the decision, which is the result of a year-long investigation.
The senator could still be subject to disciplinary measures taken by the Senate ethics committee.
Mr Ensign lawyers have said that the Department of Justice has "informed that Senator Ensign was no longer the subject of the investigation and that he did not intend to maintain any charges against him in this matter."
The Department of Justice has refrained from comment on this subject.
The announcement came as a surprise to many ethics lawyers outside the Department of Justice, that there is significant evidence that Mr Ensign federal criminal would have conspired to violate a ban on lobbying.
Interviews, e-mails and other documents, first reported in the New York Times in October 2009, indicated that Mr Ensign helped Douglas Hampton, who was one of his assistants, to obtain a lucrative lobbying work for the silence of Mr. Hampton and his wife, Cynthia, relating to the case of Senator with it.
Mrs Hampton once served as treasurer at a campaign of Ensign.
Mr Ensign has contacted a number of political donors to find work for Mr. Hampton and, then, he has defended their rights after they have committed Mr Hampton for lobbying for them, according to documents and interviews.
Given that Mr. Hampton had recently been a collaborator of Mr Ensign, he was prohibited by law for a year of his former employer lobby or the Senate as a whole.
The ethics experts have argued that the unusual agreement between Mr Ensign and Mr Hampton, who were close friends before the case, seems to be in contradiction with the absolute ban of the revolving door of lobbying.
According to the evidence that has been made public, "there seems to be a prima facie case of a conspiracy to violate and substantial violation of the law of the revolving door," said Stanley Brand, a Washington lawyer who specializes in the defence of clients in an investigation by the government.
Although the department judge has refused to explain the reasoning behind the decision in the case Ensign, Mr Brand and other ethics lawyers have said that the department seemed to be wary of political prosecutions after a number of setbacks cashed by its section of the public integrity, including the decision last year to abandon the proceedings against the former senator Ted Stevens accused of lack of prosecution.
Federal prosecutors are clearly afraid to take up arms, said Melanie Sloan, the Director General of the citizens for Responsibility and Ethics in Washington, a group that received several complaints against Mr Ensign in the case.
"this basically says high-ranking government officials can now take the laws don't apply to them," she added.
Paul Coggins, Mr Ensign Senior Counsel, said in an interview that he had received on Monday a telephone call from a prosecutor of the Department of Justice and the next day, saying that the department did not seek charges against his client.
The team of lawyers from Mr Ensign had cooperated with prosecutors to try to persuade them that the senator, as his office has reaffirmed on Wednesday in a press release, "had acted in accordance with the law."
Mr Coggins refused to specify the legal arguments that he had made the prosecution.
"I am not comfortable to go into the details of my discussions with the Department of Justice, except to say that we believe that they have made the right decision," at-il said.
Last month, the Federal Elections Commission has decided to abandon an independent investigation following a complaint by the ethics committee, claiming that the payment of $96,000 by the parents of Mr Ensign Hampton violated federal election law.
The electoral commission has said that she did not have sufficient evidence to prove that the money was anything but a gift.
NV Energy, a major company of Nevada, which has long supported Senator, is a company for which Mr Ensign has helped Mr. Hampton find work of lobbying.
An e-mail sent in December 2008 showed that, after the company has welcomed Mr Hampton as a lobbyist, Mr Ensign's chief of staff, John Lopez, contacted Mr Hampton and told him that he "martelait" the Department of the Interior on an issue.
Mr Ensign has also participated in a lunch with Mr Hampton and another client of Nevada, Allegiant Air, and he asked the secretary of transportation to set a meeting on behalf of the airline following Mr Hampton lobbying.
When the news of the case have surfaced last year, Mr Ensign has apologised to his constituents and resigned from his post as a fourth Republican leader in the Senate.
After having maintained a low profile for several months, Mr Ensign said two weeks ago that he intends to run for a third term in the Senate.
In announcing that Mr Ensign was the target of a criminal investigation, his spokesman, Jennifer Cooper, said he hoped that the ethics committee would quickly follow the example of the Department of Justice and would put an end to its investigation.
Senator Ensign looks forward to continuing its hard work on behalf of the people of Nevada, "she says.
The appeal of Cheshire will flow to Twitter
A dozen of them were ticking away in the rows of the courtroom.
They were all the minutes of the reports of horrific testimonies via Twitter.
In the end, the defence has said that there were more than 140 000 messages on the trial of the case of rape and children to bed in a house that has been burnt down.
On Thursday, widely adopted the trial of Steven J. Hayes, who was convicted of the murder of three members of the family in Connecticut, Cheshire, should lead to a formal end where the judge would impose the death penalty, adopted by the board.
But Mr. Hayes' lawyers have already put forward arguments to the court that outlines elements of appeal, likely to be the courts for years.
This is of course is that the intense reports on the trial - as well as the widespread use and extended by journalists of the Twitter - have created a "circus atmosphere," a spokin saturation and instant with inflammatory details that the board has been influenced by the public passions.
Demand could push the appeal judges to debate on the question of whether the new technologies require new rules in the courtrooms.
"I have experience in this trial; I think there is a real danger, the introduction of new technologies in the courtrooms violates the rights of the person to a fair trial," said Thomas J. Ullmann, Mr. Hayes' lawyer, chief lawyer.
The trial judge, Jon C. Blue of the Superior Court of State, has laconically bulldozing over last week rejected the claims in the decision, saying that the media were "carefully controlled" and that there was no evidence that the board would have been inspired by the passion.
But that does not seem to be the last word on the issue.
The appellate courts recognized for decades that the media coverage of notorious cases may raise questions about the fairness of a trial.
In a landmark 1966 ruling, the Supreme Court of the United States has overturned the conviction of a Cleveland osteopaths, Dr. Sam Sheppard, for the murder of his wife, supporting in its decision that there was a "carnival atmosphere at the trial" because of the media.
The crime is considered by some to have been the inspiration for the television and film "The fugitive."
Some lawyers have said that the courts of appeal for review half a century later the condemnation of Mr Hayes can be curious given the argument that new rules might be necessary to manage the communication of courtrooms, unimaginable at the time of the case of Dr Sheppard.
"there is a general right to worry about the impact of new media in large-scale trials," said John J. Donohue III, a professor at Stanford Law School who has studied the death penalty in Connecticut and wrote a report that it has been applied arbitrarily.
Professor Donohue says that some appeal judges could be intrigued by the idea that the limitation of the instant communication from courtrooms could allow fairer trial.
The case of Twitter is only one of many described by lawyers of Mr. Hayes, likely to be discussed for years; what is delaying the implementation.
Defence lawyers also said, for example, that Mr. Hayes would have suffered damage when the Blue judge refused to allow them to test the reactions of potential jurors macabre photographs of criminal scenes in the selection of the jury.
Some of the jurors said they had been horrified by the photos of victims, Jennifer Hawke-Petit, 48 years, and his daughters, Hayley, 17, and Michaela, 11 years.
Defence lawyers say they will also contest the constitutionality of the death penalty and that they will support that the judge has unjustly expelled one of juror, who had been critical to the prosecutors, and he has improperly put pressure for a verdict in taking the unusual decision to get the board to discuss in a weekend.
The jurors were not sequestered.
But their arguments on the effect of the intense media coverage of the trial could be the largest source of interest.
They noted in a protest against the verdict, filed last month, that the case has dominated the media scene in Connecticut and it was discussed during the election campaign by the candidates for the post of governor and Senate of the United States.
They have maintained that the computer media are changing and fanning the flames of the emotion of the case.
"the daily scramble of media tweets, cameras and journalists in front of the palace of justice," the lawyers wrote, "looked like nothing of what has been seen before here, in New Haven, and perhaps even at the national level."
Their focus on the coverage of the Twitter system is controversial.
In the interviews, some journalists have said that the claim that the new instant were more inflammatory than the communiqués issued more slowly, was a luddiste which would impoverish the policy of the future Court governing the media coverage of the trial.
But some lawyers have said that the courts of appeal étaitent often lured by the arguments that social and technological changes require an adaptation by the courts.
Mr Hayes' lawyers insist on this claim.
In their case, they are a reference to the decision of the Supreme Court of 1966 who had overthrown the condemnation of Dr Sheppard in because of the media coverage of the trial, and they have said they invoqueraient the need for new rules for the new media.
"this case," écrivaient-ils ," is that of Sheppard v. Maxwell of the 21 th century."
The civility can bring the divisions?
After a campaign marked by invective and the negativity, a minimum of civility erupted in Washington this week.
Is it a harbinger of a genuine bipartisan cooperation forward or an illusory moment before the rapid return to the partisan fight in the sex-capital?
Tuesday's meeting between President Obama and the leaders of the Congress has produced no breakthrough on the major issues that must be dealt with in the course of the "lame duck" session.
But, of course, there are at least had a polite discussion on the differences between the two parties, as well as on the recognition of their shared responsibilities to govern, rather than another episode where each side wanted to score points. vacuum rating point supporter.
The public meeting on Wednesday of the Committee on the president's deficit was equally civilised, despite the political differences between the States.
It seems clear that the close interaction of several months has created a mutual respect across the ideological divide, but which, however, still divides the members.
It is barely enough to declare that a new era of cooperation arrived.
The two parties are now in a period of testing and of mutual test for signs of cooperation and compromise, while trying to assess the limits of public opinion and the patience of voters for a renewed partisan war.
That is why the meeting on Tuesday and the subsequent comments of the participants have unveiled a minimum requirements or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too big and too deep to suggest a rapid change of climate which has existed in the past two years.
Whether taxation, spending, health care or the rights, the two parties remain miles away.
However, the election of November had WCT-WPPT Washington, at least in the short term.
"there is no doubt that things have changed on the tone," said Pete Wehner, an official of the Bush administration, now at the side of the Ethics and Public Policy Centre.
"it is inevitable after the elections.
The elections are causing partisan passions and, secondly, they are estomptent.
This is good. "
On some issues, including those on the agenda of the "lame duck" session, Republicans and Democrats have no choice but to find a solution.
Bush's tax cuts expire at the end of the year, and no one is in favour of that.
The two sides to find a way to preserve some or all, of a permanent or temporary.
Similarly, a compromise is possible on the extension of unemployment benefits, if only because the administrations--Republican cannot afford to give the impression that they are in favour of tax cuts for the rich, while refusing the unemployment benefits to the unemployed workers.
After the meeting on Tuesday at the White House, more optimism over a possible agreement on the issues raised during the "lame duck" session, with the ratification of the pact "New START."
But William Galston of the Brookings Institution, warned that a fruitful cooperation on the most pressing problems of the session "blade duck" does not necessarily ménera to better understanding between the two parties when the 112 th Congress convenes in January.
Instead, he says, a period of disagreement is likely, even inevitable.
"once the things that need to be made, the psychology in the short term will return to the behavioiural confrontations," he said.
Wehner has also expressed its scepticism widely shared that civility would lead to genuine cooperation.
"I think most of what happens between now and 2012 as a pré-spectacle or shadow-boxing compared to the main event of 2012, at-il said.
The reasons are closely related to the composition of the new Republican majority in the House and the voters at the tea who contributed to its creation.
However, the Republican leaders are aware of the dangers if they go too far, they know they must try to live up to their promises to reduce public spending and to repeal the new health care law.
These lines are already clear in the initial reactions to the recommendations of the Committee of the deficit which include to reform the tax code and to increase certain taxes, to raise the retirement age and reduce spending.
The co-presidents Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles chose one of the most difficult tasks in Washington and have, by themselves, imposed the deficit issue on the public agenda in a way that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes to the committee, composed of 18 members, to make their plan as an official recommendation, and they have struggled to reach this number.
The strongest resistance remains among the elected representatives of the group, which suggests that there is on tax issues, today at least, little or willingness to compromise.
It provides for two phases in the fighting between the White House and Republicans in Congress.
The first will come next year in the form of partisan battles, given that Republicans assail Obama in terms of budget, tax and health care; and then be followed by a period of bipartisan cooperation.
What would be the cause of change?
Public opinion.
It is demonstrated that, despite the partisanship of the recent election, a majority of Americans still wants to see the two parties to work together.
If the confrontation leads to a deadlock, as in 1995, then the two parties will look carefully at the public reaction.
Those who will be judged in loss will have to change course and find compromises.
But this would be an optimistic point of view.
The partisanship and polarization are greater today than they were in the mid-1990 s and it seems to be a more ideological splits between Obama and congressional Republicans than there were between President Bill Clinton and the Republicans.
At the same time, the two parties activists see 2010 as a mere prelude to a more consistent election in 2012.
Given this reality, the civility exposed this week could be appreciated by many Americans.
But it will take much more effort on the part of both parties to find common ground on the issues that still divide.
The American documents disclosed describe Moscow as a haven of corruption
The control of the city is in the hands of a " Kleptocratie " and up to the Kremlin part of bribes and protection money, said the US embassy in Russia in a note in February.
The police and the Federal Security Service are making huge racketeering which helps to explain the high cost of living in Moscow, he said.
They collect money not only legitimate businesses but also of organized criminal groups.
Each layer of bureaucracy - what Prime Minister Vladimir Putin has called the "vertical of power" - takes its share so that money snakes to the top of the scale.
The memo, which was sent to Washington under the name of the Ambassador John Beyrle, was posted on Wednesday by Wikileaks on its Web site.
The note is based on sources whose names have been cleared up.
It has been drafted while Yuri Luzhkov was still mayor of Moscow; and it is largely responsible for corruption.
It has been dismissed in October by President Dmitry Medvedev but there has been little evidence of cleaning.
Luzhkov and his wife, Elena Batourina, who owns a construction company, have always denied the accusations of corruption over the years, and he has won a libel case on these charges.
In September, he said to a Russian television station, when he was interviewed on a documentary suggesting he was corrupt: "It is crazy, it is to throw, that is nonsense."
The Russians, by an overwhelming majority, believe that their society is corrupt; according to the polls.
But it is unusual to find the information contained in a report of embassy; and it is incredible that this would be to diplomats from a foreign country to do so.
The direct link between the government of the city of Moscow and crime has led some people in the name of "dysfunctional" and to say that the government was working as a kleptocracy rather than a government, "according to the notes of the embassy.
"criminal elements" krysha " (a term used in the criminal world / the mafia which literally means" roof "or protection) that passes through the police, the Federal Security Service (FSB), the Department of the Interior (MVD) and the prosecutor's office, as well as throughout the bureaucracy of the government of the city of Moscow.
"analysts to identify a three-tier structure in the criminal world of Moscow."
"Luzhkov is at the summit."
"the FSB, the MVD and militias are at the second level."
"finally, ordinary criminals and corrupt inspectors are at the lowest level."
"it is an inefficient system in which criminal groups fills a gap in certain areas where the city does not provide some services."
The report indicates that the FSB has earned the money of larger companies and that the police are targeting small.
A source, he said, "explained that business owners of Moscow understood that it was preferable to obtain the protection of the FSB and MVD (rather than organized crime groups) because, not only, they have more weapons, more resources and more power than the criminal groups, but they are also protected by the law."
"that is why the application of protection by criminal gangs is no longer as high."
The note said that, although the collection of money should be extended, the protection itself may be uneven; even those who pay are sometimes subject to arrest.
Those who do not pay quickly see their close affairs under one pretext or another.
Medvedev has repeatedly addressed the fight against corruption, but he admitted the little progress.
The note of the embassy reports of men who bring suitcases, probably commercial-operation money, to the Kremlin.
In its fight against corruption, "Medvedev depends on bureaucrats," said in a recent interview Gueorgui Satarov, director of the "think tank Indem" of Moscow.
"but it is part of this tape."
"it is not part of a political class because it is not happening in Russia."
Without politics, without opposition, separation of powers, he said, corruption is inevitable.
According to the Indem, the costs of corruption, to the whole of Russia, would amount to more than $300 billion per year.
The country was ranked 154 th in a recent survey on the overall perception of corruption by the non-governmental organization Transparency International (the countries are ranked from least to most corrupt).
The disclosure of the note of the US Embassy, which was carried out only yesterday, late in the evening, Moscow time, remuera with certainty of discontent within the Russian government; although Luzhkov, to a certain extent, can be blamed for the failures of Moscow, this could be the opportunity for the Kremlin to show that it is in the process of resolving the problem.
Interviewed by CNN's Larry King, Putin has suggested that the WikiLeaks documents could be a manufacturing and reacted with anger over what US diplomats had disclosed in the appellant Batman and Robin bringing Medvedev.
"the problem is based on the fact that it is our interaction, an important factor in domestic policy in this country," he says.
"but to be honest with you, we do not suspect that this would be done with such arrogance, such pressure and, you know, in opposition to the ethics."
The veterans of the Khmer Rouge forced to confront the past
In a poorly informed classroom with low-quality concrete walls warships, the director of secondary school of Anlong Veng referred to the man who had built, the last leader of the Khmer Rouge, Ta Mok.
"everyone here like Ta Mok."
"it was a good leader; and it cared of its people," said Sreng Kor Ma, 42 years of age.
Known as "the butcher" for its brutality, when he was the head of the Khmer Rouge commander, remains popular in this isolated former Khmer Rouge stronghold in northwestern Cambodia where it has built hospitals, bridges and other infrastructure; and where thousands of former soldiers of the organization still live today.
But this year, 12 years after the Khmer Rouge surrendered to the government, the longstanding loyalty is finally called into question at Anlong Veng.
In April, a local forum of truth and reconciliation has allowed the victims to respond publicly to people who participated in the regime.
In June, the government has distributed a handbook of high school, for the first time, history teaches the Khmer Rouge to the children of its former soldiers.
And, in July, a Cambodian court, together with the United Nations, made its first sentence for a former member of the Khmer Rouge, condemning, to 35 years in prison, the former head of the notorious torture centre of Tuol Sleng, Kaing Khek Iev, better known as the "Duch."
In this situation, the anxiety has increased among veterans of the Khmer Rouge Anlong Veng; making reconciliation efforts and their wills of Cambodian reintegrate into society.
"there is some resentment and fear among the former Khmer Rouge but they are powerless to do anything," said Chhang Youk, director of the Documentation Centre of Cambodia, an independent organization that conducts research on the regime.
"for them, life under the Khmer Rouge was glorious but the regime has become a symbol of evil."
"the situation creates divisions within families."
Under the reign of the Khmer Rouge in Cambodia, from 1975 to 1979, approximately 1.7 million people were executed or died of hunger, disease or overwork.
When the Vietnamese invaded and toppled the government of Pol Pot-Unis in 1979, the rest of the regime and its army have fled to Cambodia's border with Thailand.
There, they have launched an insurgency that lasted until the last movements in December 1998.
While Pol Pot, Nuon Chea and Ieng Sary ran the guerrillas from their bases in the mountains of the West of Cambodia and in the jungle, Ta Mok was preparing a response to Anlong Veng.
But in the mid-1990 s, after a peace agreement sponsored by the United Nations has led to the country's first democratic elections in 1993, large groups of Khmer Rouge fighters began to make defection to the government, culminating with Ieng Sary capitulated in 1996 and of Nuon Chea and Samphan in 1998.
Pol Pot died of natural causes in 1998 and Ta Mok, who had stood up, was captured by government forces in 1999 in the mountains near to Dangrek.
He died in prison in Phnom Penh in 2006 pending his trial.
Without their benefactors, most of the veterans of the Khmer Rouge have sunk into grinding poverty, common to the rural areas of Cambodia; and many people are nostalgic for the movement.
Although a few elite officers of the Khmer Rouge have kept their local leadership posts in exchange for tabling the weapons, it is unskilled farmers on low rank and file.
"these people have benefited from very little follow-up after the capitulation," said Sok Leang Centre for justice and reconciliation which organizes public forums throughout Cambodia, including Anlong Veng.
"they are imbibés agrarian utopian ideology of the regime."
"they have been high in a framework where business is a foreign concept."
SOR Lim, 55 years of age, who joined the Khmer Rouge as a teenager in 1974, has fought in the jungle around Anlong Veng before moving in 1998 as poor--but rice grower.
"life under the Khmer Rouge was good," he said.
"your Mok has everyone."
But now, life is difficult because we must meet our own needs. "
The Khmer Rouge Tribunal has also caused concern here.
At the beginning of next year, the court should begin the judgement of Samphan, Nuon Chea, Ieng Sary and his wife, Ieng Thirith Khmer Rouge, another former minister.
The court's mandate is to judge the senior leaders and those most responsible for crimes but he has not said if it went beyond these four cases.
More may be needed to calm the fears to Anlong Veng.
The latest media speculation turned to Im Chaem, aged 64, former head of district in the province of Banteay Meanchey under the Khmer Rouge in the 1970 s.
In 2007, she said researchers of the Documentation Centre of Cambodia that she had supervised the construction of Trapeang Thma, a project which forced thousands of workers were killed.
Recently, at a torrid evening, Im Chaem labour is the scope of its wooden house on pilotis, on a dirt road outside of Anlong Veng.
While the sun scorched throwing long shadows on the grass, Im Chaem refused to discuss his role in the Khmer Rouge.
If the court had convened, "she says, she would refuse to go.
"Cambodia is at peace and stable," is there said.
"if there is more prosecution, there will be war."
The Prime Minister Hun Sen, who has done defection of Khmer Rouge in 1978, has also repeatedly warned that instability would occur if the court had several suspects; although the experts and historians disagree about that.
"Cambodia should dig a hole and bury the past, at-il said.
But the past is what Cambodia needs to do to move forward, said Youk Chhang, documentation centre.
"reconciliation in Khmer terms is to reconnect the pieces," he says.
"we need to put these pieces together so that we can understand."
The center has produced the first handbook approved by the government on the Khmer Rouge, "A History of the Democratic Kampuchea regime, consisting of 75 pages."
It has distributed to Anlong Veng in June as a supplement to the history books of the Department of Education, designed for high schools, which contained less than four pages on the Khmer Rouge.
As in most of Cambodia, the young people of Anlong Veng know only a few details about the Khmer Rouge, in spite of the city's ties to the regime.
Touch Valeak, 19 -year-old student at the high school of Anlong Veng, said that the new manual helps students to understand an important part of their history.
But his parents have reacted with scepticism when he returned home to study with the book.
"my family rejects many parts of the manual and the court," he says.
"they are suspicious because they do not know exactly how many people the court will continue."
Such resistance has made the process of reconciliation complex and difficult, "said Sok Leang.
But the public forums, the manual and the court are beginning to have an impact, at-il said.
However, the Khmer Rouge to retain a powerful atrait here.
In the mountains of Dangrek, a path, invaded by weeds and littered with plastic bags, led to a rectangle of black soot, covered with a roof of corrugated rouillée.
The body of Pol Pot was burned on a pile of tyres after his death in 1998.
Nuom Sothea, aged 31, a saleswoman of mobile phone roadside, said she did not know much about the man who was cremated at this location.
"but it has a great spirit; and many people go there to pray," she says.
It was the anniversary of Nuom Sothea and, later that day, she planned to walk to the last resting place of Pol Pot, where it would leave a bouquet of ripe bananas in the hope of bringing the chance.
Belarus to give up its stock of weapons-grade uranium
The government of Belarus announced on Wednesday that it would abandon its stockpile of highly enriched uranium, a key component for nuclear weapons; this décison is part of a surprise victory of President Obama's campaign to secure nuclear materials around the world
The agreement was disclosed in a joint communiqué issued after the Secretary of State Hillary Rodham Clinton met here the Belarus Foreign Minister, Sergei Martynov, on the sidelines of a summit on security.
The US government had tried for years to convince the Belarus to renounce the highly enriched uranium and seemed to have reached the horizon last spring.
But US officials told the Washington Post that some classified operations have been carried out with Belarus in the past two months to eliminate 187 pounds of weapons-grade uranium from a research centre in Belarus.
This has opened the way for an agreement on Wednesday to eliminate the rest of the field of about 500 books, according to an official who spoke on the condition of anonymity because of the sensitivity of the issue.
The agreement appears to be one of the most important results of the Nuclear Security Summit of 47 nations, organized at the initiative of Obama; where Belarus was excluded.
Apparently, it was good to obtain an invitation to the former Soviet republic following the summit, in 2012.
"I am really fascinated by the fact that they want a seat at the Nuclear Security Summit of 2012 nuclear security summit."
"it proves that this process works," said Ken Luongo, president of the Partnership for global security, a group of promotion of nuclear safety.
Clinton called the agreement "very significant and important step" by Belarus.
Obama is committed to Prague in April 2009 to secure all vulnerable nuclear materials around the world in the next four years.
Since then, the US government has helped six countries to get rid of their highly enriched uranium.
Belarus would be the seventh.
A dozen countries have done under the administration of George W. Bush.
At the time of Obama's nuclear security summit, the president of Belarus, Alexander Lukashenko, said that the nation will never agree to its uranium.
"we have kept hundreds of kilograms of highly enriched uranium, which is essentially of weapons-grade uranium and the low-enriched uranium," said Mr Lukashenko.
"it is our product... We are not going to make dirty bombs, and we will sell it to anyone."
"we are going to use it for research purposes, that is all."
The Belarus has moved to the United States a few months ago; however, expressing an interest in reaching an agreement.
The first implementation to eliminate uranium of Belarus, in October, has been particularly complicated because the material was slightly spent, indicated.
It was posted on a special train which has more than 1 300 miles to a facility in Russia to be stored and eliminated, said officials.
The second operation has been completed on Monday and was carried out by air, according to the officials.
The US government has spent $13 million in its efforts, in large part to replace the research facilities of the Belarus with low-enriched uranium; unsuitable for weapons.
"careful coordination and organization have been implemented in order to strengthen confidence, leading to the agreement signed by Clinton," said Andrew Bieniawski, an official from the Department of Energy Reduction of the Impending World.
According to estimates by the Centre for the Study of Nonprolifération James Martin, Belarus had this year at least 88 pounds of weapons-grade uranium, as well as hundreds of kilograms of highly enriched uranium.
Belarus is seeking to eliminate its stockpile by 2012, according to a joint statement.
The relations between Belarus and the United States are strained for years, mainly due to the harsh repression by Lukashenko of Human Rights.
But the statement on Wednesday suggested a potential revival.
"while welcomimg progress on these issues of global security, the United States and Belarus have recognized that greater respect for democracy and human rights in Belarus were essential to improve bilateral relations; and essential to the progress of the country and its citizens," she said.
