The Pakistani nuclear program generates a great concern in the U.S.
Islamabad product of atomic weapons to "a faster pace than any other country."
The filtrations Wikileaks confirms to the connection between the Taliban and Pakistan.
The content of the correspondence between the US embassy in Pakistan and the United States Department of State filtered by the portal Wikileaks confirms the enormous preoccupation in Washington on Pakistan's nuclear program.
Apart from the details revealing and tasty offered on the content of the conversations and thoughts of North American diplomatic representatives accredited in Islamabad, the documents reveal that the cooperation between the two countries in the field of nuclear safety, instead of increasing, "decline" and that the unstable Asian country producing nuclear weapons "at a faster pace than any other country in the world."
The peculiarity of the Pakistani nuclear program - the fact that the weapons are not assemblies, but they are emmagasinnées by components to make difficult destruction in case of attack - is one of the main reasons for concern in Washington.
That is how the ambassador to Pakistan, Anne W. Patterson, lists in a report before the visit of former National Security Advisor James Jones: "The proximity of certain nuclear installations of the territory under Taliban attack, the dispersal of nuclear materials and the vulnerability of the transport of nuclear materials."
The large number of people involved in the nuclear arsenals and missile programmes is envisaged, not only by the United States, but also by Russia, as proliferation-proof and a reason to maintain custody.
"Pakistan has to hire staff with strict religious beliefs to protect nuclear facilities; given the decline of educational and cultural levels, the extremist organisations have more opportunities to recruit people who work in the nuclear or missile programmes" the expert said Yuri Korolev, of the Ministry of Externes Russian during a meeting with his American counterparts.
The new documentation filtered by the portal of Julian Assange is increasingly reduced cooperation between the United States and Pakistan in the field of nuclear proliferation and the Pakistani high degree of production of nuclear armas.
A report by the Embassy in May, which describes as "frustrating" communication with Pakistan, supports the following: "Transparency is frequently non-existent; the offers of help remain unanswered or are eliminated."
In another message, Peter Lavoy, an official of the National Intelligence for South Asia, notes that "despite the economic disaster, Pakistan producing nuclear weapons at a faster pace than any other country in the world."
Ambassador Patterson also calls in Washington, during a visit by the head of the Army, Gen. Ashfaq Kayani, he made it "very clear" to "the Pakistan Army must come with the tacit support to terrorist groups."
Hunting of the head of Wikileaks
Obama nombrera to a high responsible for the fight against terrorism in order to avoid the new infiltrations.
Interpol makes a red alert to track the movements to Assange.
All the aspects linked to WikiLeaks and its founder, Julian Assange, form a complicated labyrinth where it is difficult to have certainty on the facts.
Yesterday Interpol has issued a "red alert" to "locate and track the movements of Assange."
However, it is not a traditional arrest order.
In addition, it is not new, but it datte on 20 November.
And it has nothing to even with the latest filtration of more than a quarter million diplomatic documents but with the accusations of sexual abuse that the Australian faces in Sweden.
In addition, counsel creator of Wikileaks, Mark Stephens, ensures that "the police know where and how to contact Mr Assange."
The 20 international police force with the headquarters in Lyon (France) has dictated the agenda to request of Sweden, but he has not made public until yesterday, after having received permission from the authorities of this country.
As well, the 188 countries of Interpol received the indication to identify or locate Assange "for his arrest provisionnelle and his extradition."
Even if Interpol cannot give the order to arrest a person affected by a red alert, many member countries, according to the explanations of the organization, consider the appeal red notice a free lane for the arrest and the police - the national body, especially if they have a bilateral extradition agreement, as is the case of Sweden and England, where Assange.
The movement was outraged to Assange's lawyers, who have published a letter dénonceant yesterday that the WikiLeaks founder, 39 years, has shown itself willing to answer questions via video-conference.
They also recall that Assange has sought and obtained the prosecutor's permit to get out of Sweden, compared to the famous Lavrentiy Pavlovich Beria, head of the security of Stalin.
"it seems to be a fighter, not a legal persecution," denounces the missive.
As the world seeks - and Australia his mother defends his son's innocence - Assange continues to be in a place not unknown, but it is silent.
On Monday he gave at an unknown location an interview to the Director of the Time magazine through Skype, a conversation in which he requested the resignation of the United States Secretary of State, Hillary Clinton.
"if we can show that it was responsible for giving orders to the American graduates that they épient at the United Nations by violating international treaties that the United States has signed, it should resign," he says.
His opinion was insulted yesterday by the White House press secretary, Robert Gibbs, who has described as "ridiculous and absurd" calling for the resignation.
"I am not sure why the opinion of a type with a web page should focus," déclaré-t-il for CNN.
Obama himself has appointed a High Commissioner of combating terrorism, Rusell Travers, to prevent further leaks of documents.
The test of President Barack Obama's spokesman to reduce the importance of Assange contrasts with the views that politicians and conservative commentators proclaim these days.
Peter King, Congressman from January will chair the Committee of National Security in the Dutch Lower Chamber has asked the Department of State it is studying the possibility of including Wikileaks in the list of terrorist organisations "to confiscate its funds and continue to any person who provide contributions or assistance."
Even further went Tom Flanagan, an adviser of the Canadian chairman Stephen Harper, who has come back to his statements after he said that Assange will "be murdered."
"Obama should turn it into objective and use a plane without crew or something similar."
A person who has not asked for an apology was Mike Huckabee, Baptist minister, ex-gouverneur of Arkansas and possible candidate for the presidency.
"in the Government who leaked the information is guilty of treason and everything that is not an execution would be too kind a punishment," déclaré-t-il for Fox.
