"I am standing with a party that has created the granite stones taken under your feet," said the Liberal leader Michael Ignatieff, while he was surrounded by Members after the weekly meeting of the caucus.
Liberals argue that the bill as proposed, which would hold a year any person from a ship identified as carrying illegal immigrants, would violate the Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms.
The leader of the Bloc Québécois, Gilles Duceppe, has also indicated that it could not support the bill, because it is the wrong target.
"we are against and it seems that all the opposition parties are against, so we will see what the government will do," said Mr Duceppe.
The criticism of the NDP on immigration, Olivia Chow, has discounted the criticism that his party is not tough enough on illegal immigrants.
"the New Democrats agree to take measures against smugglers of illegal immigrants and that is what we are doing through another bill, C- 35," said Mrs Chow.
"we do not support the bill of the Conservatives because it takes to refugees and imprisons children for at least a year," said Mrs Chow.
The immigration minister Jason Kenney, has accused the opposition parties to play politics and to ignore the will of Canadians.
"Canadians overwhelmingly say that they do not tolerate this kind of illegal migration, these criminal operations targeting Canada and which treat the country as a doormat."
"they expect Canada take firm action," the Minister responded Kenney.
The government has not announced a vote of confidence on his bill, which could have brought the country to elections in its rejection.
A conservative QMI Agency has however said that the government would seek a vote for every Member who oppose is then explained to the electorate.
