Rivers under strict surveillance
Several rivers remain under close surveillance because of heavy rainfall which hit several regions of the province since Tuesday.
A landslide occurred on Wednesday afternoon, in Shawinigan, in the Mauricie region.
Two homes have been evacuated as a preventive measure.
In the evening, another shift occurred in Saint-Lin-Laurentides, in Lanaudière.
A road is collapsing.
From Tuesday to Wednesday evening, heavy rainfall hit several regions, from 40 to 70 millimetres of rain.
Additional 20 to 40 millimetres of rain were expected by Thursday evening, according to the regions.
The north of the river and sectors in the Valley were the most affected.
They could receive up to 100 millimetres of rain.
As these rainfall should add to the melting of the snow already accumulated in some sectors, the spillover of several rivers.
Flood alert warnings have been issued on Wednesday evening by the Quebec civil security for the rivers Ouareau and Achigan, Lanaudière.
The rivers of the north of Saint Geronimo, in the Laurentian, and the Chêne, in Lotbinière, were the subject of old flood and remained under surveillance.
In the Lanaudière region had, the heavy rainfall have led the spillover of some lakes, to Sainte-Julienne, Sainte-Marcelline-de-Kildare and Rawdon.
To Saint-Calixte, a temporary bridge has been brought down because of heavy rain.
Ten homes were evacuated by preventive measure.
In the Outaouais, the spillover of some lakes has led to the closure of several, including in the municipality of Mansfield-et-Pontefract.
The civil security remains on alert and is monitoring the situation closely, "said Annik Bouchard, security advisor.
The Centre for flood forecasting of Quebec has issued Wednesday of severe flood warnings for several rivers, including Maskinongé, The Assumption, Ouareau, Achigan, Batiscan and Nero.
Dupont partially blamé
The Quebec radio personality Stéphane Dupont has undergone a partial setback to the Canadian Council of broadcasting standards (non-CCNR) for controversial remarks on social assistance and the Haitians and on its crude on-air language.
The non-CCNR judge that Mr Dupont and his team of CHOI 98.1 FM had the right to express their views, but that some comments contained "inaccurate information on social assistance, unduly negative representations of Haitians and rude language which is not the broadcasts during the day."
The Council also concluded that a discussion on suicide, including the dissemination of the names of two people who had taken their own lives, do not have violated the codes on broadcasting.
The non-CCNR had received several complaints about comments made during broadcasts between 2008 and 2010.
The first decision was made following a complaint of the Common Front of social assistance recipients of Quebec.
The group complained that the amounts cited in the show were inaccurate.
The facilitators must submit solid information rather than misleading.
On suicide, the facilitator Stéphane Dupont had estimated that suicide is a gesture of cowardly.
The majority of the members of the Committee have concluded that the message was that the suicide should not be seen as a solution to the problems of life.
"the majority of the Committee considers that the episodes of" Dupont noon "have touched a sensitive issue in a fair and appropriate manner."
No blame has been accepted.
The last was statements that followed the earthquake in Haiti.
Mr Dupont and Jean-René Dufort media were delivered to a showdown privately-retained reaction.
The facilitator of CHOI said that there was no donation to help Haitians because we could not know with certainty that the really needy people would receive the money.
The Committee believes that these comments were not abusive, but their cumulative effect is an unduly negative representation of Haitians.
"I have already served my suspension of three days."
"my record is free for a year and a half," said the facilitator.
In all the decisions PRGAA denounces the dissemination of rude language.
In each case, the broadcaster CHOI-FM worked "beyond its obligation."
The consequences are minimal for the station which, among other things, must announce these decisions once during prime-time hours within three days.
