More green, but frankly sceptical.
The Quebec consumer makes very little confidence to the sustainable development, but also fair trade marks and qualifications écologisantes to guide their choices.
Worse, even if he lives in a media universe where messages in favour of a more responsible consumption are rampant, there is a lack of credible information, a failure that he calls of brake on its commitment, indicates the Baromètre of responsible consumption, the first reading was delivered yesterday.
Even if they have increased the so-called socially responsible consumption of products in 2010, Quebeckers appear to give very little credit to those who are trying to sell.
Two thirds of them say they do not believe the environmental performance of companies like green advertising companies, reveals the measurement tool developed by the Monitoring Centre of responsible consumption of Sherbrooke University.
Another observation: half of consumers have doubts about the reliability of official qualifications secured to the so-called fair products, but also of the credibility of products and brands become as parties involved, Baromètre.
In the same vein, the politicians' rhetoric on this issue is taken seriously by only 14.6% of Quebecers.
However, responsible consumption seems essential to stimulate this information currently part of the lively consumption by almost a third of Quebec consumers.
Indeed, the vacuum and the dubious nature of the information calmeraient the ardour of 46% of consumers.
This is the second brake identified by the Baromètre, after the higher price of these products.
In addition, a third of Quebecers are well-publicized alleged performance of green products or services sought to put in the hands.
On another note, consumers have been nearly half in 2010 to have changed their habit and above all changed one or more products to meet their conviction.
Up to 61%, they have also fostered purchases from traders of their neighbourhoods and privileged the purchase of food products grown in their region, Baromètre.
Greener and responsible - CWGBI of responsible consumption reached 64 on a maximum of 100 for this year - the Homo consumus Quebec likes to present himself as the king of recycling which seeks to reduce its environmental footprint in concerned about the protection of animals.
But its social and ecological conscience seems to remain outside of his car, Baromètre indicates: in 2010, barely 28% of Quebecers indicated using public transportation or have advocated green car-pooling to defend their interests.
Walking and cycling have also been supported by 39.1 percent of the participants in this vast behavioral investigation, which has just taken its first cliché.
