The United States are therefore, he concludes, "the proverbial elephant in this election: omnipresent, but potentially too threatening to talk about it."
The ambassador understands even less this "deafening silence" that the two countries have an intense political and economic relationship.
"logically, he believes, the ability of a candidate, a party and even more of a party leader to manage this critical relationship should be a key factor that the voters have in mind by voting."
Another expression of that feeling of importance reads in the cable sent on 22 January 2009 by Terry Breese, in Ottawa, President Barack Obama preparing for his first visit to Ottawa.
"your trip will help to ensure the survival of the government at the beginning of February vote of confidence on the federal budget, for which Canada will post its first deficit in more than a decade because of a recovery plan of $30 billion to $40 billion," Mr. Breese writing.
