A global plan to renovate lighting
The United Nations has proposed yesterday in Cancún a renovation plan for the industrial, commercial and domestic lighting in 100 countries in order to obtain a reduction of greenhouse gases (GHG), which represents a third of the additional reduction that remains to be done to stabilize the climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan is in the process of large concrete projects that the United Nations hope to adopt in Cancun to compensate for the lack of binding commitments by industrialized countries.
According to the plan tabled yesterday, if the incandescent light bulbs that still monopolise from 50 to 70% of the market were replaced by fluorescents or, better, light bulbs by light bulbs to light-emitting diodes (LEDs or "LED" in English), the bulk of the 1.8 billion tonnes (gigatonnes GHG) expressed on the planet for humans would be avoided.
The lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
That is the equivalent of 70% of global emissions of the cars.
In Copenhagen, the last year, the major emitters, such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, engaged in voluntary plans that should put the global emissions of greenhouse gases to 53 gigatonnes to 49 gigatonnes.
But still it out of this 5 gigatonnes by 2020 in order to stabilize the rising to 2 degrees Centigrade climate in order to avoid it gets out of control.
In the incandescent light bulbs, 95% of energy is dissipated in the form of heat and the rest, 5%, product of the light.
Fluorescents, the light bulbs with energy expenditure is reduced by 75% and with the new light bulbs to LEDs, this need network-energy twice.
The bulbs fluorescents last on average from 6000 to 10 000 hours.
The new LEDs bulbs, such as those that initiated the Philips manufacturing this week - the company has also participated in the study of the United Nations - have a life expectancy of 25 000 hours and consume 80% less energy than a light bulb is heating, which gives an idea of the possible economy with a plan that would apply to 100 countries.
These new light bulbs can also work with rhéostats in addition to making very little heat.
And they do not contain mercury.
Several experts have expressed reservations about light bulbs fluorescents because they contain mercury and we need to eliminate them as hazardous waste, which is not always possible in developing countries, except if the guidelines are in place.
But, says the report, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not the light bulb fluocompacte, but rather the coal-fired power plants, which emit a lot of mercury to produce electricity wasted in incandescent light bulbs.
Only the United States, these plants produce 25 000 tonnes of mercury per year.
The report details the gains that each country through this program.
For example, Indonesia would save a billion dollars per year in purchases of electricity and eight million tonnes of CO2, the equivalent of 3.5 power stations whose construction would cost 2.5 billion.
The Ivory Coast is waiting in the nervousness the announcement of election results
"without delay" the Secretary General of the United Nations, Ban Ki-moon, has called for the publication of the results of the presidential election in Côte d'Ivoire, after the expiry of the deadlines.
"the Secretary General stresses the need for the Independent Electoral Commission to complete its work and to announce the interim results without further delay," said a spokesman for the head of the United Nations. "
"it calls on all Ivorian parties and institutions to act responsibly and refrain from any action until the announcement of preliminary results."
Despite pressure from some foreign governments, the electoral commission has missed the deadline of midnight on Wednesday without publish the results, three days after the vote on Sunday.
About forty minutes before the expiry of the deadline, the chairman of the CIS said on television that the Committee "continued to work" to announce the results.
The calls have multiplied Wednesday in the world for the CIS states finally the name of the winner of the run-off between incumbent Laurent Gbagbo and Alassane Ouattara.
But the Gbagbo camp is counting on the annulment by the Constitutional Council of fraudulent votes "in the north, held by the ex-rebellion New Forces (National Front) since the failed coup of September 2002.
Pascal Affi Guessan, campaign manager of the Ivorian president, said that the intimidation of voters by the National Front in the north of the country had deterred the supporters of the outgoing president to vote.
The election could be cancelled if the complaints by Gbagbo are adopted by the Constitutional Council.
The opponents of Gbagbo felt that the country's highest court is not neutral because it is headed by Paul Yao N Dré, a close political ally of Gbagbo.
North Alassane Ouattara, a man who denies any link with the former rebels, has deemed "unacceptable" the delay in the announcement of results and asked Gbagbo to respect them, but it did not go so far as to call for the victory.
His allies say that Gbagbo has blocked the publication of the results because he knows he has lost and that lodge a complaint with the Constitutional Council, after having prevented the electoral commission to disseminate the results, would be illegal.
The second round of the presidential election on Sunday, was supposed to complete the process of reunification and reconciliation to a country remained split into two for years.
The United Nations warned Wednesday the Ivorian political class that it could be held responsible for any violence.
Laurent Gbagbo had finished at the top of the first round, on 31 October, 38% to 32% Alassane Ouattara, who has received public support for the former president Henri Konan Bédié (25% in the first round).
The unemployment rate has remained stable in France in the 3 th quarter
The unemployment rate in France within the meaning of the International Labour Office (ILO) has remained stable at 9.3% in mainland France (9.7% in the overseas departments), show the provisional data corrected for seasonal variations (CVS) published on Thursday by the Insee.
The number of unemployed to 2.631 million in mainland France.
Data from the second quarter have been confirmed in 9.3% of the active population in mainland France and 9.7% with the French overseas departments.
A year on, the unemployment rate is rising by 0.1 percentage point.
More broadly, 3.4 million people in metropolitan France did not work in the third quarter but wanted to work, whether or not available in the two weeks to work and that they are looking for a job or not.
The situation of young people on the labour market has deteriorated, with a further increase in the rate of unemployment, increased to 24.2% in mainland France (+ 0.9 point on three months, + 0.5 point on a year) and 25% by including the overseas departments.
In the third quarter, 637 000 young people aged 15 to 24 were unemployed in the sense of the ILO.
Older people have experienced a slight rise in unemployment, to 6.4% in mainland France (+ 0.2 point on three months and a year), 482 000 people from 50 years or more, and 6.6% with the French overseas departments.
Only 25-49 years have benefited from a stability of unemployment in the third quarter, to 8.3% in mainland France (0.1 point on three months, + 0.1 point on a year) and 8.8% in France.
The Insee silent for monthly unemployment rate since 2006, after an argument on the method of calculation.
Eurostat, the European Union's statistics agency, continues to do so and announced on Tuesday a rate of 9.8% for France (DOM included) in October after 9.9% in September.
