Clotilde Reiss affair: the Élysée Palace has exaggerated the mediation of Syria
For more than ten months, from July 2009 to May 2010, the fate of the young French researcher Clotilde Reiss, arrested in Iran for "espionage," held the opinion in suspense in France, diplomacy, and increased the deterioration of relations between Paris and Tehran.
Everything under the watchful eye of US diplomats.
The American documents obtained by WikiLeaks and consulted by Le Monde reveal some of this crisis.
They describe how the Elysée Palace explained its strategy to Americans, to give them advice for the treatment of their own "hostages" in Iran (a small group of hikers).
They show how French officials have sought to convince Washington that the release of the young French woman did not have to return for the release of Majid Kakavand, an Iranian man detained in France and sought by US justice for trafficking of materials for the benefit of the Iranian nuclear programme.
Finally, they place under a harsh light the way in which the French Presidency has sought to manipulate the media to promote the idea that the Syrian president, Bashar al-Assad, had played a central role in the release of Clotilde Reiss.
In reality, there was nothing.
A diplomatic telegram on 12 August 2009 in Paris is entitled "Iran: French comments on the way to deal with cases of hostages."
The Elysée adviser for strategic affairs, François Richier, accompanied by the director of the Quai d'Orsay to North Africa and the Middle East, Patrice Paoli, interact with the American diplomat Kathleen Allegrone.
They explain the French method.
They advise the Americans to do the same to repatriate their own nationals being held in Iran.
"made of noise," they say, "martelez constantly" in the media the words "fundamental human rights," "innocence," "immediate release."
It matters to embarrass the Iranian regime, sensitive to its image.
"do this all the more that the Iranians ask you not to do so."
Because, past attempts of discussions by discreet channels, "the silence will solve nothing," the Iranians are "masters in delaying tactics."
Mr Richier adds that the arrest of foreigners is "an Iranian tactic familiar: the taking of hostages for political blackmail."
He announced that the release of Clotilde Reiss prison (who will speak on August 16, when it takes refuge in the embassy of France "will require the payment to the Iranians of a large sum of money" See- (€230 000).
And he noted that the Élysée Palace anticipate other crises of hostages, a phenomenon that "going to get worse."
The Iranians could "in the near future to stop another of some 1 800 French citizens living in Iran," he says.
28 August 2009.
Clotilde Reiss is released from prison since twelve days, but remains blocked in Iran.
Information is disseminated: Iran's Majid Kakavand, including the US extradition claim for an illegal trafficking of sensitive electronic equipment to Iran, is released in Paris by decision of a judge.
The US Embassy, as many observers, is mulling over this troubling coincidence.
For Washington, which is tracking down illegal networks Iran's acquisition of material aimed at the nuclear programme, the enlargement of Majid Khakavand is bad news.
France has accepted a bargain?
The release of the Iranian against that of the French?
In a new interview with Kathleen Allegrone, on September 4, François Richier ensures that this is not the case.
The Elysée Palace, he says, not only has "been completely taken by surprise by the judge's decision," but has sought to oppose it.
"there were loud exchanges between the French Presidency and the Attorney-General" (at the time, Michèle Alliot-Marie), but "the French government may not go back on the judicial decision," drift.
Mr Richier also wants to demonstrate that Majid Kakavand IYJS remains under the supervision of French intelligence services "close."
The adviser of the Elysée Palace a phone number, clutching, then informed the American diplomat that Iran is currently located in buildings in Paris managed by the Iranian Embassy. "
During the detention of Clotilde Reiss in Iran, the Elysée Palace is sparing no effort, by means of releases and "leaks" in the media, to make people believe that the Syrian President Bashar al-Assad plays an important role "" and "impact" of "Ombudsman."
The Americans are watching this activity without irony, and find that the manipulation is bearing fruit as several press articles reflected the official French version.
A telegram dated August 25, 2009 evokes "the French official media blitz."
What is at the heart of both expressed "gratitude" to Mr Assad, wondered the Embassy in Paris.
"despite their statements full of praise, French officials privately admit that they have only a vague notion of what the Syrians have actually done."
The paper then focuses on the reasons that led the Elysée Palace to pay in this fiction.
The intense effort of communication "aims to validate the Sarkozy's policy of opening to Syria," that analyses.
A policy launched in 2008, "which was perceived by many critics in France and abroad, as premature and undeservedly."
In "exaggerating the Syrian role," Paris seeks to demonstrate to Syria "what praises it can draw in playing a constructive role in the region."
The aim is to "sow the seeds of discord between Syria and Iran."
The US Embassy knows of good source.
On August 11, François Richier told him: "Of course, we do not know whether the Syrians have done anything."
"but we thank you."
"this should at least cause confusion among Iranians."
Clotilde Reiss go in France on May 16, 2010.
Nicolas Sarkozy received at the Elysée Palace.
In a statement, he thanked the presidents of Brazil, Senegal, and Syria, for their "active role for the release of our compatriot."
No online games for young Koreans past midnight
The South Korean government will adopt a so-called "Cinderella" law which will ban for adolescents to play online games after midnight by blocking their access, said government officials.
A bill will be submitted to Parliament in December to ask companies to online games to block access to these games after midnight, young people under the age of 16 years, said representatives of ministries of culture and the family.
"a lot of children were playing these games all night and then difficulties at school and to have a normal life during the day."
"we believe that this law is necessary to ensure their health and their right to sleep," said AFP Jo Rin, the Ministerial responsible in charge of the bill.
The online games will be accessible to 6 hours of the morning.
Companies will have a year to prepare for the application of the law, he said.
The government also intends to ask companies to limit the time daily access to these games for young people whose parents request, the official added.
It will also be made available to people who are demanding free software which limit the time spent on the Internet.
South Korea is one of the most "connected" countries and the T4008 newspapers regularly news related to an intensive use of the Internet.
The country is also an undisputed champion of online gaming world competition.
In November, South Korea had won four gold medals at the World Cyber movie, about 58 other nations.
