One certainty: the ECB will keep its main interest rate unchanged at 1%, its lowest level since May 2009.
In the facts, the Treasury bond purchases by the ECB last week have doubled, to almost 1.35 billion euros.
And, according to the indiscretions of market operators, it would have made new purchases of Irish and Portuguese securities, yesterday.
In total, the central banks of the Eurosystem have bought for 67 billion euros since May 2010.
Among the market operators, the expectations of a further purchases are no doubt (see page 29).
Economists do not expect a significant change of course.
If the loans to more than three months have already disappeared from the arsenal of the ECB, the latter is still in careprovider unlimited liquidity on generous terms and for periods from one week to three months.
Economists now expect that to be extended for a few months.
"I cannot imagine that it significantly amend its program."
"if not, it would take the risk of tensions in the short term," said Michael Schubert, Commerzbank economist.
"a gradual phasing-out announced during the first quarter of 2011 seems more likely," anticipates Norbert Bräms, economist at Sal.
Oppenheim.
On the SENAME plan on the public debt market, "the ECB should maintain a purchasing volume of these obligations to tackle a sluggish market," says Norbert Bräms.
Given the importance of the exposure of European banks to the markets of the euro zone sovereign debt, the has no other choice but to maintain its presence on the market.
"it needs to replace the lack of investors in the market and act to prevent a runaway yields paid by even the most fragile," has an important bond manager yesterday.
Because if interest rates are high, the Member will be all the more embarrassed to reduce their debt, if not stabilize.
The protection of the euro is the price.
